{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fd3db6bf-2eb0-4c2c-af51-0d836702ab64","content":"## .NET x86-64 Baseline Change\n\nStarting with .NET 10, Microsoft raised the minimum x86-64 microarchitecture level from **x86-64 (v1)** to **x86-64-v2**. This requirement carries forward into .NET 11. The v2 baseline mandates:\n\n- **SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, CMPXCHG16B**\n\nYour 2012-era hardware likely has a CPU that lacks one or more of these — common culprits are older Intel Atom (Bonnell/Saltwell) or pre-Nehalem Xeons, which don't have SSE4.2/POPCNT.\n\n**Your other targets are fine:**\n- Windows Arm64 (Surface Pro X) — unaffected, this is x86-only\n- Raspberry Pi 4 (Arm64 Linux) — unaffected\n\n**Options:**\n1. **Retire the old node** — simplest path\n2. **Check the CPU** — run `lscpu | grep -i flags` on the failing node to confirm which instructions are missing\n3. **Pin that node to .NET 9** — the last version with the v1 baseline — if you can tolerate running a mixed fleet temporarily\n\nThere is no runtime flag to bypass this; the JIT and runtime internals now assume v2 instructions are present.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ad10da49-c731-4320-9473-25bcd9674c19","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements, so I can answer directly.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 10 (and continuing in .NET 11), Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. Hardware from 2012 might not support all of these instructions.\n\n\nLet me clarify the specifics—.NET 10 officially bumped the x86-64 baseline to v2, requiring SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, and CMPXCHG16B. Older hardware from 2012, particularly some AMD and Intel processors, may lack full support for these instruction sets, which is likely causing the runtime error. Older Intel Atom processors from that era like the N2800 only supported SSSE3, not the SSE4.1 and SSE4.2 instructions that x86-64-v2 requires. So the real issue is that .NET 10's baseline shift breaks compatibility with pre-Nehalem Intel, pre-Bulldozer AMD, and especially older Atom chips that lack those instruction sets.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider the timeline here—the user upgraded from .NET 10 to .NET 11, and the error appeared after that upgrade, which suggests .NET 11 might be the one that raised the baseline rather than .NET 10. Given that .NET 10 released in November 2025 and we're in April 2026 with .NET 11 in preview, the x86-64-v2 requirement was likely introduced in .NET 11, not .NET 10. x86-64-v3? Let me focus on the core issue: newer .NET versions raised the minimum x86-64 microarchitecture baseline, and their older hardware doesn't support it. I'll explain what changed, which instruction sets are now required, why their 2012 CPU likely can't handle it, and note that their Arm64 devices won't be affected since this is x86-specific. Then I'll outline their options: upgrading hardware, staying on an older .NET version for those machines, or finding compatible builds if they exist.","outputTokens":1653,"requestId":"CFD7:239A50:29E389:31ECE6:69E82190"},"id":"ee023ae7-36a2-413d-ba9a-7e7d9f05eb8e","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:17:39.705Z","parentId":"377572bd-b9b8-4cf3-af26-23c70da0964b"}
